{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TU7FPFzdrfVVu6oLfKsYRo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Confirmed: mongodb-replica-1 is PRIMARY, mongodb-replica-0 and mongodb-replica-2 are SECONDARY.\n\nNow I need to:\n1. Update the ConfigMap with the new settings:\n   - verbosity: 3 (was 2)\n   - slowOpThresholdMs: 800 (was 400)\n   - journalCompressor: zlib (was snappy)\n\n2. Do a rolling restart, but for data safety:\n   - Restart secondaries (replica-0 and replica-2) first\n   - Then step down the primary (replica-1) and restart it\n\nThe default rolling restart would restart from highest to lowest ordinal, which means the primary gets restarted before the secondaries—not ideal for safety. Instead, I'll manually restart replica-2 and replica-0 first, wait for them to be ready, then step down the primary to trigger an election before restarting replica-1.\n\nActually, thinking through the StatefulSet behavior more carefully: with `OrderedReady` policy, the restart goes replica-2 → replica-1 → replica-0. Since we have three members, the replica set maintains quorum as long as two are up. So replica-2 restarts first while replica-0 and replica-1 stay running, then replica-1 restarts while replica-0 and the recovering replica-2 can elect a new primary, and finally replica-0 restarts last. This actually works out safely without needing manual intervention.\n\nI should use `kubectl rollout restart` to handle this automatically rather than manually deleting pods, though I need to be aware that WiredTiger journal compression changes only take effect when a new journal file is created, not immediately on restart. will be flushed to disk, so the new journal files created after restart will use zlib compression. I should update the ConfigMap, perform a rolling restart, and then monitor to verify everything works correctly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usag